Master Interview Syllabus & Complete Q&A

Based solely on the interview history, here is an exhaustive syllabus that breaks down every topic into its smallest sub‑topics, followed by precise answers to each of the 110+ questions.

---

Syllabus – Topic‑Wise Deep Dive (Beginner → Advanced)

1. Java Core & Java 8

· Streams API
  · Creating streams (collection.stream(), Arrays.stream(), Stream.of())
  · Intermediate operations (filter, map, flatMap, sorted, distinct, peek, limit, skip) – lazy
  · Terminal operations (collect, forEach, reduce, count, findFirst, anyMatch) – eager
  · Collectors:
    · toList(), toSet(), toMap(), joining()
    · groupingBy(classifier) → Map<K, List<V>>
    · groupingBy(classifier, downstreamCollector) e.g., groupingBy(..., counting()) → Map<K, Long>
    · groupingBy(classifier, mapFactory, downstreamCollector) for custom map type
  · Collectors.toList() in parallel streams: preserves encounter order if the stream is ordered (e.g., from a List), implementation not guaranteed (usually ArrayList)
  · parallelStream(): uses ForkJoinPool, beware of shared mutable state
· Exceptions
  · Checked (Exception subclasses except RuntimeException) vs Unchecked (RuntimeException, Error)
  · try-catch-finally; finally always executes
  · Suppressed exceptions: when finally throws, the original exception becomes suppressed (accessible via getSuppressed())
· Functional Interfaces
  · @FunctionalInterface annotation – optional, ensures single abstract method
  · Built‑in: Predicate<T>, Consumer<T>, Function<T,R>, Supplier<T>
  · Composing predicates: Predicate.and(), or(), negate() vs writing one monolithic lambda – readability/maintainability
· Supplier in parallel streams: Supplier.get() provides a new instance per call, allowing per‑thread accumulators (thread‑safe)

2. Spring Boot

· Starters
  · Concept: curated dependency sets (spring-boot-starter-web, etc.)
  · Risks: dependency bloat, version conflicts, unexpected auto‑configuration
· Bean Configuration
  · @Component (classpath scanning) vs @Bean (explicit declaration in @Configuration)
  · @Autowired, @Qualifier, @Primary
  · Scope: singleton (default), prototype, request, session
· Singleton Pitfalls
  · Single instance shared across all threads → mutable state causes race conditions (e.g., HashMap as cache)
  · Fix: use ConcurrentHashMap, or a proper caching layer (Redis, Caffeine)
· Dependency Injection Issues
  · NullPointerException when a constructor parameter is null: missing bean definition, the class not being a Spring component, or circular dependency
· Web Layer
  · @RequestParam: required by default; use defaultValue = "0" to supply a fallback
  · PUT vs PATCH: PUT replaces entire resource (idempotent); PATCH applies partial updates
  · @RestController = @Controller + @ResponseBody (every method returns data directly)

3. Spring Data JPA & Hibernate

· Fetching Strategies
  · Lazy (loaded on first access) vs Eager (loaded immediately)
  · Defaults: @OneToMany, @ManyToMany → LAZY; @ManyToOne, @OneToOne → EAGER
· Associations & Mappings
  · @OneToOne: owning side holds foreign key via @JoinColumn
  · @ManyToMany pitfalls: hidden join table can cause cascade deadlocks → explicit join entity (e.g., UserRole) preferred
  · Cascade types: PERSIST, MERGE, REMOVE, REFRESH, DETACH, ALL
· Querying & N+1 Problem
  · N+1: one query for parent, N queries for children
  · Solutions: JOIN FETCH (per‑query), @EntityGraph (reusable), @BatchSize (batch loading)
  · DTO Projection: select only needed fields into a DTO
  · JOIN FETCH + pagination: Hibernate loads all rows and pages in memory → MultipleBagFetchException / ClassCastException
    · Workaround: two‑query approach (paginate IDs first, then fetch with JOIN FETCH IN (:ids)); or cursor‑based pagination
· Pagination
  · Offset (LIMIT/OFFSET) – simple, but unstable when data changes (duplicate/missing records)
  · Cursor‑based (WHERE id > :lastId ORDER BY id LIMIT :size) – stable with changing data
  · Spring Data JPA Pagination: Pageable + Page<T> abstraction
· Transactions
  · @Transactional ensures atomicity; missing it causes partial commits, duplicate orders
  · Should enforce uniqueness at DB level (constraints) and use idempotency keys for duplicate prevention
· Performance with Large Collections
  · Avoid mapping huge collections in JPA; query them separately with pagination
  · Batch processing, batch fetching
· Native Queries – result must match entity structure; otherwise ClassCastException, use @SqlResultSetMapping if needed
· JPQL Fetch Join Pagination Bug – directly using setFirstResult/setMaxResults with fetch join on collection → in‑memory pagination; avoid it

4. REST APIs

· @RequestParam defaults, required flag
· PUT vs PATCH
· Pagination strategies: offset, cursor
· Spring Data REST pagination with Pageable

5. JUnit 5 & Mockito

· JUnit 5 Assertions.assertEquals()
· Mockito: verify(), if method not invoked → WantedButNotInvoked
· Throwing exceptions: doThrow(...).when(mock) / when(...).thenThrow(...)
· Verifying catch block: mock dependency to throw, then assert fallback or verify another mock
· @RunWith(MockitoJUnitRunner.class) (JUnit 4) initializes @Mock; JUnit 5 uses @ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)

6. Kafka

· Poison message handling: DLQ, skip‑and‑log, retry with backoff then DLQ
· Schema Registry upgrade: use FULL compatibility during transition, upgrade clients, then restore desired level
· Nullable Avro field addition: add field with default (e.g., null), old consumers ignore extra fields
· Schema Registry purpose: centralise schemas, enforce compatibility, version history
· Producer key bug: null/constant key → all messages to same partition → ordering lost
· AdminClient partition count vs UI: may show replication factor; refresh metadata
· Under‑replicated partitions: compare replicas vs isr via describeTopics()
· ISR: In‑Sync Replicas – replicas fully caught up with leader; acks=all waits for all ISR

7. Avro

· Compatibility types: BACKWARD, FORWARD, FULL
· Nullable fields: adding a nullable union with default is forward compatible
· Default values required for forward compatibility

8. Transactions

· Missing @Transactional leads to partial commits
· Duplicate order prevention: idempotency token + unique database constraint
· Idempotency: same result regardless of repetition
· Retry handling: implement idempotency first, then retry with exponential backoff

9. Concurrency

· Singleton beans: stateless or use thread‑safe structures (ConcurrentHashMap)
· ConcurrentHashMap: thread‑safe map with fine‑grained locking
· Supplier in parallel streams: per‑thread instances → thread‑safe
· Parallel stream ordering: ordered sources preserve order; unordered do not
· Spring bean thread safety: prefer stateless; else synchronise or use @Scope("prototype")

10. Performance

· Large collections: paginate at DB level; avoid loading all
· Batch processing: use chunk‑based (Spring Batch)
· Deadlocks: consistent lock order; redesign with explicit join entities
· Join table redesign: replace @ManyToMany with explicit entity
· Memory: DTO projections, lazy fetch, pagination
· Query: indexes, avoid SELECT *, @BatchSize
· Cache: eviction policy (LRU/LFU/TTL), size limit, distributed cache

11. System Design Scenarios

· High‑traffic cache inconsistency → distributed cache with write‑through/invalidation
· Bulk role deactivation → paginated batch updates
· Fetch join pagination → two‑query approach (paginate IDs, then fetch full entities)
· Large collection → query separately with pagination
· Duplicate order → idempotency key + unique constraint
· Stable pagination → cursor‑based
· Join table redesign → explicit join entity
· Retry‑safe APIs → idempotency
· High concurrency transactions → optimistic locking (@Version) + retry

