Complete Q&A

Java Core & Java 8

Q1. Write a Java function to group a list by its first character and return a Map.

```java
public Map<Character, List<String>> groupByFirstChar(List<String> list) {
    return list.stream()
        .filter(s -> s != null && !s.isEmpty())
        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(s -> s.charAt(0)));
}
```

Q2. Which intermediate operation transforms stream elements?
map() (and flatMap()).

Q3. Explain intermediate vs terminal operations in Java Streams.
Intermediate operations are lazy and return a stream; terminal operations trigger the pipeline and produce a result or side‑effect.

Q4. What is Collectors.groupingBy()?
A collector that groups elements by a classifier function into a Map. Overloads support downstream collectors and map suppliers.

Q5. What happens when Collectors.groupingBy() is used with a downstream collector like Collectors.counting()?
It counts the number of elements in each group, returning a Map<K, Long>.

Q6. Explain Collectors.toList() in parallel streams. Does it guarantee list implementation or ordering?
It preserves encounter order if the stream is ordered (e.g., from a List). The list implementation is not guaranteed (usually ArrayList).

Q7. What is the output of: parallelStream().map(n -> n).collect(Collectors.toList())?
The list contains the same elements as the source, in encounter order (since the source is ordered).

Q8. Explain checked vs unchecked exceptions.
Checked exceptions (e.g., IOException) must be caught or declared. Unchecked exceptions (RuntimeException subclasses) are not forced by the compiler.

Q9. What happens if both the try block and the finally block throw exceptions?
The finally exception overrides the original; the original becomes a suppressed exception (accessible via getSuppressed()).

Q10. What is the role of @FunctionalInterface? Is it required?
It marks an interface as functional (exactly one abstract method). Not required, but provides compile‑time safety.

Q11. Explain composing predicates using Predicate.and() vs writing one large predicate.
and() allows composing smaller, reusable predicates, improving readability. Functionally equivalent.

Q12. Explain why using Supplier<StringBuilder> in parallel streams is thread‑safe.
Each thread receives a new StringBuilder from Supplier.get(), so there is no shared mutable state.

Spring Boot

Q13. What are Spring Boot Starters?
Curated dependency descriptors (e.g., spring-boot-starter-web) that bundle compatible libraries.

Q14. What risks do Spring Boot Starters introduce?
Dependency bloat, version conflicts if overridden, and unexpected auto‑configuration.

Q15. @Component vs @Bean
@Component – class‑level, detected by scanning. @Bean – method‑level in @Configuration, for explicit bean creation.

Q16. Singleton beans with HashMap causing inconsistent cache values. Diagnose and fix.
Multiple threads modify the shared HashMap → race condition. Fix: use ConcurrentHashMap or a dedicated cache (Redis/Caffeine).

Q17. Constructor parameter is null at runtime causing NullPointerException. Identify the cause.
The dependency is not a Spring bean (missing @Component, etc.) or there is no matching bean definition.

Q18. How do you make @RequestParam default to zero?
@RequestParam(defaultValue = "0") int param

Q19. PUT vs PATCH.
PUT replaces the entire resource (idempotent); PATCH applies partial updates.

Q20. @RestController vs @Controller.
@RestController = @Controller + @ResponseBody (methods return data directly, not view names).

Spring Data JPA & Hibernate

Q21. Lazy vs Eager Fetch.
Lazy loads on first access; eager loads immediately with the parent.

Q22. Default fetch types.
@ManyToOne, @OneToOne → EAGER; @OneToMany, @ManyToMany → LAZY.

Q23. Explain @OneToOne mapping.
Defines a 1:1 relationship; the owning side holds @JoinColumn with the foreign key.

Q24. Many‑to‑many join table causing deadlocks during bulk delete. Diagnose and redesign.
Deadlocks from inconsistent lock order on join table. Redesign with an explicit join entity (e.g., UserRole), delete join entities first.

Q25. Why does JOIN FETCH + pagination fail?
Hibernate must load all rows and paginate in memory; can throw MultipleBagFetchException.

Q26. Explain Hibernate runtime exceptions with fetch join pagination.
QueryException or MultipleBagFetchException when using setFirstResult/setMaxResults with JOIN FETCH on a collection.

Q27. How should you paginate fetched associations safely?
Paginate parent IDs first (SELECT id … LIMIT ?), then fetch full entities with JOIN FETCH WHERE id IN (:ids). Or use @BatchSize.

Q28. Why is Spring Data JPA Pagination useful?
It standardises pagination with Pageable/Page, handling SQL LIMIT/OFFSET and total count queries.

Q29. Best practices for handling very large collections in JPA.
Do not map them as a JPA collection; instead, query the related entities separately with pagination.

Q30. Missing @Transactional causes duplicate orders and partial inserts. Fix?
Wrap the entire operation in @Transactional and enforce uniqueness at the database level (unique constraint on order reference).

Q31. Offset pagination causing duplicate/missing records while data changes.
Use cursor‑based pagination (WHERE id > :lastId ORDER BY id LIMIT :size).

Q32. Native query mapped to entity throws ClassCastException.
The native query must return exactly the columns expected by the entity. Use @SqlResultSetMapping for complex mappings.

Q33. Find the bug in JPQL Fetch Join pagination.
Using setFirstResult/setMaxResults with JOIN FETCH on a collection forces in‑memory pagination → exceptions. Avoid fetch join with pagination.

Q34. Explain N+1 problem.
One query for the parent entity, then N additional queries for each child when lazy collections are accessed.

Q35. EntityGraph vs Fetch Join.
@EntityGraph is reusable; JOIN FETCH is per‑query. Both can solve N+1.

Q36. DTO Projection.
Select only needed fields into a plain DTO object, reducing data transfer and memory usage.

Q37. Batch Fetching.
@BatchSize or hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size loads collections in batches when one is accessed, reducing N+1.

Q38. Cascade types.
PERSIST, MERGE, REMOVE, REFRESH, DETACH, ALL – control propagation of operations to child entities.

Q39. Join Entity instead of @ManyToMany.
Create an explicit entity for the join table (e.g., UserRole) to gain control over extra columns, pagination, and avoid deadlocks.

REST APIs

Q40. Default @RequestParam.
Parameters are required by default; if missing, Spring throws MissingServletRequestParameterException.

Q41. PUT vs PATCH. (already answered)

Q42. Pagination API.
Use Spring Data's Pageable interface and return Page<T>.

Q43. Cursor Pagination.
Uses a unique, sequential column (e.g., id) and a WHERE clause to fetch the next page stably: WHERE id > :lastId ORDER BY id LIMIT :size.

Q44. Offset Pagination.
Uses LIMIT and OFFSET; simple but can cause duplicate/missing records when data changes concurrently.

JUnit 5 & Mockito

Q45. Which class provides assertEquals()?
org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions (JUnit 5).

Q46. What happens if verify() is called but the method was never invoked?
Mockito throws WantedButNotInvoked (a MockitoAssertionError).

