Kafka

Q50. Three approaches to handle poison messages.

1. Send to Dead Letter Queue (DLQ) after retries.
2. Skip and log the message, commit offset.
3. Retry with exponential backoff, then DLQ.

Q51. Safe Schema Registry upgrade plan.
Temporarily set compatibility to FULL, upgrade all producers/consumers, then restore desired compatibility.

Q52. Consumer failing after nullable Avro field added.
The new field must have a default value (e.g., "default": null). Older consumers ignore the unknown field.

Q53. Why does Schema Registry help?
Centralises schemas, enforces compatibility checks, and stores schema history.

Q54. Producer key bug affecting ordering.
If the key is null or constant, all messages go to one partition → ordering across partitions is lost. Use a proper key.

Q55. Kafka AdminClient reports different partition counts than UI.
The UI may be showing replication factor rather than partitions. Refresh metadata to get correct count.

Q56. Detect under‑replicated partitions.
Use kafka-topics --describe or AdminClient.describeTopics(); compare the isr list size to the expected replication factor.

Q57. ISR (In‑Sync Replica).
The set of replicas fully caught up with the leader. With acks=all, a write succeeds only when all ISR members acknowledge it.

Avro

Q58. Nullable field compatibility.
Adding a nullable field (union with null) that has a default value is forward compatible.

Q59. Backward Compatibility.
New schema can read data written with the old schema.

Q60. Forward Compatibility.
Old schema can read data written with the new schema (requires default values for new fields).

Q61. Full Compatibility.
Both backward and forward compatible.

Q62. Default values.
Every field must have a "default" to allow schema evolution (especially forward compatibility).

Transactions

Q63. Missing @Transactional.
Without @Transactional, each operation runs in its own transaction → partial commits possible. Annotate the service method with @Transactional.

Q64. Duplicate order prevention.
Use an idempotency key (e.g., client‑generated UUID) together with a unique database constraint.

Q65. Idempotency.
An operation that produces the same result no matter how many times it is executed.

Q66. Retry handling.
Make the operation idempotent first, then retry with exponential backoff on transient failures.

Concurrency

Q67. Singleton thread safety.
Singleton beans must be stateless or use thread‑safe structures (ConcurrentHashMap). Otherwise, race conditions occur.

Q68. ConcurrentHashMap.
A thread‑safe map that allows concurrent reads and writes without external synchronisation.

Q69. Supplier in parallel streams.
Supplier.get() returns a new instance per invocation; when used in a collector, each thread gets its own accumulator → thread‑safe.

Q70. Parallel Stream ordering.
For ordered sources (e.g., ArrayList), encounter order is preserved. For unordered sources (e.g., HashSet), order is not guaranteed.

Q71. Thread safety in Spring Beans.
Prefer stateless beans. If stateful, use @Scope("prototype") or synchronise access properly.

Performance

Q72. Handling very large collections.
Paginate at the database level; never load entire collections into memory.

Q73. Batch processing.
Use Spring Batch or chunk‑based processing to reduce memory footprint.

Q74. Deadlocks.
Caused by inconsistent lock acquisition order. Ensure consistent ordering, redesign many‑to‑many with explicit join entity.

Q75. Join table redesign.
Replace @ManyToMany with an explicit join entity (e.g., UserRole) to control deletes and avoid lock issues.

Q76. Memory optimization.
Use DTO projections, lazy loading, and pagination to minimise the object graph.

Q77. Query optimization.
Add indexes, avoid SELECT *, analyse execution plans, use batch fetching (@BatchSize).

Q78. Cache optimization.
Choose an eviction policy (LRU/LFU/TTL), set size limits, and invalidate on writes.

System Design Scenarios

Q79. High traffic shared cache inconsistency.
Use a distributed cache (e.g., Redis) with write‑through or cache‑aside and proper invalidation.

Q80. Bulk role deactivation.
Process users in paginated batches, updating a limited number of rows per batch.

Q81. Fetch Join pagination.
Paginate IDs first, then fetch full entities with JOIN FETCH using the IDs. Avoid fetch join with pagination.

Q82. Large collection design.
Do not map the collection in JPA; query the associated entities separately with pagination.

Q83. Duplicate order creation.
Idempotency token + unique constraint on the order reference.

Q84. Stable pagination.
Cursor‑based pagination using a unique, sequential column (WHERE id > :lastId).

Q85. Join table redesign.
Explicit join entity instead of @ManyToMany.

Q86. Retry‑safe APIs.
Implement idempotency; use a client‑generated request ID and check for duplicates.

Q87. High concurrency transaction handling.
Optimistic locking with @Version; retry on OptimisticLockException.

